So Brian's reaction to my asking him to make a few videos about cultural
values (I don't have the headspace - I'll do it later) initially depressed
me - but then I realised that this demonstrates the need for Big Spaceship's
new product:

 

*	Leaders don't have the headspace for cultural messaging at the
moment
*	Even though this is when it is most needed
*	Which could result in missteps (how many Rivel guys were wondering
about the size of Brian's house when he starts to talk about furloughing
employees?) and a lack of cultural capital being maintained and built
*	And unlike for PR, companies don't have communications directors for
staff
*	Cultural communication works best when targeted rather than
broadcast - Cambridge Analytica (arguably) demonstrated that and $400m has
followed that logic into targeted behavioural change marketing for the US
presidential election
*	SO it would be Big S's role to direct & script the cultural content,
using leaders where available
*	Indigo would highlight areas that need cultural direction, ensure
that the right cultural content is getting to the right people and quantify
the impact of cultural messaging to allow iterative improvement

 

I am thinking something similar for Lane 4 - as training increasingly goes
online and digitally targeted, the margins in providing leadership training
will collapse, but companies will still need help in directing and managing
their training and messaging channels - maybe after a while there will be an
in house expert at large companies that does this, but in the interim it
would be a perfect job for a consultant. Plus if they are getting 50% of
Indigo's ongoing income they can afford to charge less for the upfront work
now - just when companies don't want to spend......

 

C


